# BGP Peers Configuration Example
# Format: remote_asn,remote_ip,local_ip
#
# This file defines BGP peering relationships for Mellanox network interfaces.
# Peers are automatically assigned to detected Mellanox interfaces in order.
#
# Fields:
#   1. remote_asn   - Remote peer's AS number
#   2. remote_ip    - Remote peer's IP address
#   3. local_ip     - Local IP address for this interface (with /30 subnet assumed)
#
# Notes:
#   - Lines starting with # are comments and will be ignored
#   - Empty lines are ignored
#   - Whitespace around values is automatically trimmed
#   - Peers are assigned to Mellanox interfaces in detection order
#   - First peer → First Mellanox interface
#   - Second peer → Second Mellanox interface, etc.
#

# Example 1: Simple two-peer setup
# These will be assigned to the first two Mellanox interfaces detected
65100,10.0.1.1,10.0.1.2
65200,10.0.2.1,10.0.2.2

# Example 2: Multiple peers on different subnets
# 65300,192.168.1.1,192.168.1.2
# 65400,192.168.2.1,192.168.2.2
# 65500,192.168.3.1,192.168.3.2

# Example 3: High ASN numbers (4-byte ASN)
# 4200000001,10.10.1.1,10.10.1.2
# 4200000002,10.10.2.1,10.10.2.2

# Example 4: Data center fabric configuration
# Spine connections (assigned to interfaces in order)
# 65001,172.16.1.1,172.16.1.2
# 65001,172.16.2.1,172.16.2.2
# 65002,172.16.3.1,172.16.3.2
# 65002,172.16.4.1,172.16.4.2
